'''Milnrow''' (pop. 12,500) is a [[suburb]]an town within the [[Metropolitan Borough of Rochdale]], in [[Greater Manchester]], England.<ref name=miln1>{{cite web|url=http://www.credoreference.com/entry/orionbritainireland/milnrow|quote=A former cotton town in Greater Manchester|publisher=credoreference.com|work=Brewer's Britain and Ireland|title=Milnrow|year=2005|accessdate=2010-04-11}}{{Subscription required}}</ref><ref name=miln2>{{cite web|url=http://www.credoreference.com/entry/mwgeog/milnrow|publisher=credoreference.com|title=Miln<U+2022>row|work=Merriam-Webster's Geographical Dictionary|year=2007|accessdate=2010-04-11|quote=Town, Greater Manchester, NW England, SE suburb of Rochdale; pop. (2001e) 12,800.}}{{Subscription required}}</ref><ref name="GM Gazetteer">{{cite web |url=http://www.gmcro.co.uk/Guides/Gazeteer/gazzm2n.htm |title=Greater Manchester Gazetteer|publisher=Greater Manchester County Record Office|accessdate=20 June 2007|at=Places names - M to N}}</ref> It lies on the [[River Beal]] at the foothills of the [[South Pennines]], and forms a continuous urban area with [[Rochdale]]. It is {{convert|1.9|mi|km|1}} east of Rochdale's town centre, {{convert|10.4|mi|km|1}} north-northeast of the city of [[Manchester]], and spans across urban, suburban and rural locations<U+2014>from [[Windy Hill (Pennines)|Windy Hill]] in the east through to the [[Rochdale Canal]] in the west. Milnrow includes the villages of [[Tunshill]] and [[Newhey]],<ref name="RMBC32">Rochdale Metropolitan Borough Council (N.D.), p.&nbsp;32.</ref> and is adjacent to junction 21 of the [[M62 motorway]].
 
[[Historic counties of England|Historically]] a part of [[Lancashire]], Milnrow during the [[Middle Ages]] was a [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] located within the [[Butterworth (ancient township)|township of Butterworth]] and [[Rochdale (ancient parish)|parish of Rochdale]]. It was named by the [[Anglo-Saxons]], but the [[Norman conquest of England]] resulted in its ownership by minor [[Normans|Norman]] families, such as the Schofields and Cleggs. In the 15th century, the descendants of these families successfully agitated for a [[chapel of ease]] to be constructed in Milnrow by the banks of the River Beal, triggering its development as the main settlement in Butterworth. Despite this distinction, Milnrow did not increase much further in size or population until the dawn of the [[woollen]] trade in the [[Late Middle Ages]]. 

To supplement their income, the inhabitants of Milnrow entered the [[domestic system]], producing [[flannel]] and woollen cloth in purpose-built [[weavers' cottage]]s, some of which from the [[Early Modern Britain|Early Modern period]] have survived as [[listed building]]s.<ref>Frangopulo (1977), p.&nbsp;149.</ref> Coalmining and metalworking also flourished in this period, but the [[Industrial Revolution]] supplanted the domestic industries and converted Milnrow into an urban [[mill town]] that mass-produced textile goods in [[cotton mill]]s, such as [[Ellenroad Ring Mill Engine|Ellenroad Ring Mill]] (now a museum). The [[Milnrow Urban District]] was established in 1894 and was governed thereafter by its own district council until its abolition in 1974.

Milnrow has been described as "the centre of the south Lancashire dialect".<ref>Joyce (1993), p.&nbsp;198.</ref> [[John Collier (caricaturist)|John Collier]] (who wrote under the pseudonym of Tim Bobbin) was an acclaimed 18th-century caricaturist and satirical poet from Milnrow who wrote in a broad [[Lancashire dialect and accent|Lancashire dialect]]. Rochdale-born poet [[Edwin Waugh]] was influenced by Collier's work, and wrote an extensive account of Milnrow during the mid-19th century in a tribute to Collier.<ref name="Waugh"/> Although Milnrow's heavy textile industries declined during the mid-20th century, the town has continued to grow as a result of [[suburbanisation]], [[urban renewal]] and its immediate proximity to road, rail and motorway networks.

==History==
[[Neolithic]] human activity in Milnrow is evidenced with an ancient stone axe found at Hollingworth.<ref>{{cite web |title=Monument no 45988 |url=http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=45988 |publisher=Pastscape.org.uk |accessdate=2008-04-25}}</ref> [[Bronze Age|Bronze]] and [[Iron Age]] peoples left thousands of [[flint tool]]s which have been found on the moorland surrounding Milnrow, including a stone hammer found at Low Hill in 1879.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Poole | first1 = S. | year = 1986 | title = A Late Mesolithic and Early Bronze Age Site at Piethorn Brook, Milnrow | url = | journal = Greater Manchester Archaeological Journal | volume = 2 | issue = | pages = 11<U+2013>30 }}</ref> Low Hill was the site of an ancient [[Tumulus|burial mound]] where a [[urn|funerary urn]] was found. A small Roman statue of the goddess [[Victoria (mythology)|Victory]] was discovered at Tunshill Farm in 1793.<ref>{{cite web |title=Monument no 46071 |url=http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=46071 |publisher=Pastscape.org.uk |accessdate=2008-04-23}}</ref> During excavations at [[Piethorne Reservoir]] in the mid-18th century, a [[Celt]]ic spear-head with a {{convert|5|in|mm|adj=on }} blade was unearthed, implying human habitation in the locality during the [[British Iron Age]].<ref name="Bateson3">{{Harvnb|Bateson|1949|p=3}}</ref> There is no physical manifestation of the [[Anglo-Saxons]] and [[Norsemen]] in the locality, but [[British toponymy|toponymic evidence]] implies they have been present.<ref>{{cite book|title=East Lancashire Nomenclature and Rochdale Names|last=March|first=Henry Colley|year=1880|asin=B0014M51VQ|publisher=Simpkin & Co.|location=[[London]]}}</ref>
[[Image:River Beal from Milnrow Bridge.jpg|thumb|left|The [[River Beal]] flowing through Milnrow, and by its banks, former [[weavers' cottage]]s. Handloom weaving of [[woollen]]s was Milnrow's historic staple industry.]]

The name Milnrow is derived from [[Old English]],<ref name=miln1/> but its meaning has not been deciphered with any certainty. The name may be a corruption of an old pronunciation of "Millner Howe", a water driven [[Gristmill|corn mill]] at a place called Mill Hill on the [[River Beal]] that was mentioned in deeds dating from 1568.<ref name="RMBC32"/><ref name="Hignett2"/><ref name="Ekwall"/> Another explanation is that it means a "mill with a row of houses", combining the Old English elements ''myne'' and ''raw''.<ref name=miln1/> Others have suggested that the name "Milnrow" is derived from a local family with the surname Milne, who owned a row of houses in the locality. A map from 1292 shows "Milnehouses" at Milnrow's present location, other spellings have included "Mylnerowe" (1545) and "Milneraw" (1577).<ref name="Hignett2"/><ref name="Ekwall">Ekwall (1972), p.&nbsp;56.</ref> 

Milnrow emerged as a settlement after the [[Norman conquest of England]] in 1066; the [[Normans|Norman]] families of "de Butterworths", "de Turnaghs", "de Schofields", "de Birchinleghs", "de Wylds" and "Cleggs" controlled the lands which formed the [[Butterworth (ancient township)|township of Butterworth]] from which Milnrow evolved as its main settlement.<ref name="Hignett2">Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;2.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|author=[[Manchester City Council]]|url=http://www.spinningtheweb.org.uk/m_display.php?irn=240&sub=nwcotton&theme=places&crumb=Rochdale|publisher=spinningtheweb.org.uk|date=|accessdate=2008-04-20|title=Rochdale Towns}}</ref> In addition to the [[chapelry]] of Milnrow, Butterworth encompassed the [[Hamlet (place)|hamlets]] of Clegg, Wildhouse, Belfield, Butterworth Hall, Lowhouse, [[Newhey]], Ogden, [[Tunshill]], Haughs, and Bleaked-gate-cum-Roughbank.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/descriptions/entry_page.jsp?text_id=845610&word=NULL|title=Descriptive Gazetteer entry for Butterworth|publisher=visionofbritain.org.uk|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref> Butterworth was linked, ecclesiastically, with the [[Rochdale (ancient parish)|parish of Rochdale]].

During the [[Middle Ages]], the small, scattered community in and around Milnrow was primarily [[agrarian]], with the growing and milling of grain and cereal being the main labour of the people.<ref name="RMBC32"/><ref name="Hignett3">Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;3.</ref> Dry [[ironstone]] smelting was introduced in to Milnrow at a very early time as evidenced from ancient [[kiln]]s found at Tunshill.<ref name="Hignett3"/> A [[chantry]] was constructed in the year 1400 by the [[Baron Byron|Byron]]s&mdash;the then [[Lord of the Manor|Lords of the Manor]]&mdash;and a [[chapel]] for the wider community in 1496;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.link4life.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=c.showPage&pageID=1064|title=Events in Milnrow 1400 - 1929!|publisher=link4link.org|author= Rochdale Boroughwide Cultural Trust|date=|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref><ref name="Hignett32">Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;32.</ref> A document dated 20 March 1496, during the reign of [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]], proclaims that open land by the River Beal would be the site of the new chapel.<ref name="Hignett32"/>
[[Image:Butterworth Hall Mill.jpg|thumb|right|Butterworth Hall Mill was Milnrow's last [[cotton mill]].]]
Legal documents dated 1624 state that Milnrow consisted of six cottages; there were a further nine at Butterworth Hall, and three at Ogden.<ref name=fish122>{{Harvnb|Fishwick|1889|p=122}}.</ref> Milnrow did not expand until the introduction of a [[woollen]] [[weaving]] trade which began in the [[Late Middle Ages]] and continued until the 19th century.<ref name="GMArch35">McNeil, R. & Nevell, M. (2000), p.&nbsp;35.</ref><ref name=Roc33>{{Harvnb|Rochdale Metropolitan Borough Council|1985|p=33}}.</ref> During this time nearby Rochdale&mdash;the local [[market town]]&mdash;was used as a central marketing, finishing and [[fellmonger]]ing hub.<ref name="GMArch35"/> The handloom weaving of woollen cloth and [[flannel]]s in the [[domestic system]] became the staple industry of Milnrow, facilitating the community's growth and prosperity.<ref>{{Harvnb|Fishwick|1889|p=54}}.</ref> Between 40,000 and 50,000 sheep skins were needed every week to provide for Milnrow's industries,<ref>Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;10.</ref> and as early as the 16th century, the demand for [[wool]] was so great it had outstripped the local supply of the region and had to be imported from [[Lordship of Ireland|Ireland]] and the [[English Midlands]].<ref name="GMArch35"/> As a consequence of the woollen trade, rows of "fine stone domestic workshops" or [[weavers' cottage]]s were constructed beyond Milnrow's original core, with dwelling quarters on the lower floors and [[loom]]-shops on the top floor.<ref name="GMArch35"/><ref>Frangopulo (1977), p.&nbsp;29.</ref>
[[File:Weir Road, Milnrow.jpg|thumb|left|Weir Road is in the north of Milnrow, and has property dating from the town's [[suburbanisation]] during the late-20th century.]]
With the onset of the [[Industrial Revolution]], the River Beal was used to power large weaving mills.<ref name=Roc33/> Within one generation during the late-19th century,<ref name=Roc33/> and following a boom in nearby [[Oldham]], Milnrow's staple industry changed from wool weaving to [[cotton]] spinning.<ref name=Roc33/><ref>Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;11.</ref> Soon, distinctive rectangular brick-built mills dominated Milnrow's landscape.<ref>Sellers (1991), p.&nbsp;47.</ref> Milnrow, the location of some of the earliest [[ring spinning]] companies, had many of the characteristics of a [[company town]]. The Heaps of Milnrow exercised significant deferential and political influence in the local area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/1449/1/tomss4_Steve_doc_2_final.pdf|publisher=eprints.whiterose.ac.uk|format=PDF|year=2000|title=Industrial Relations and Technical Change: Profits, Wages and Costs in the Lancashire Cotton Industry, 1880-1914|author=Procter, S. & Toms, S.|accessdate=2008-04-29}}</ref> Following the [[Great Depression in the United Kingdom|Great Depression]], the region's textile sector experienced a decline until its eventual demise in the mid-20th century. Milnrow's last [[cotton mill]] was Butterworth Hall Mill, demolished in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milnrow-village.freeserve.co.uk/milnrow1.htm|publisher=milnrow-village.freeserve.co.uk|accessdate=2008-06-18|author=|title=This is Milnrow: Industry}}</ref> Milnrow experienced population growth and [[suburbanisation]] in the second half of the 20th century, spurred by the construction of the [[M62 motorway]] through the area, making Greater Manchester and [[West Yorkshire]] commutable.<ref name=Roc33/><ref name="Hignett35"/>

==Governance==
[[Image:Banded fleece of Milnrow.png|thumb|right|Although not granted by the [[College of Arms]], a "banded fleece"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gladstone.qld.gov.au/gcc/index.asp?id=75|author=Gladstone City Council|publisher=gladstone.qld.gov.au|accessdate=2008-06-16|title=Mission, logo and Crest|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080529200915/http://www.gladstone.qld.gov.au/gcc/index.asp?id=75 <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=2008-05-29}}</ref> has been an emblem of Milnrow since its former council chairman used it as a badge. The emblem alludes to Milnrow's woollen trade heritage.<ref>Rochdale Metropolitan Borough Council (N.D.), p.&nbsp;19.</ref>]]
Lying within the [[Historic counties of England|historic county boundaries]] of [[Lancashire]] since the early 12th century, Milnrow was a [[chapelry]] and component area of [[Butterworth (ancient township)|Butterworth]], an ancient [[Township (England)|township]] within the [[Rochdale (ancient parish)|parish of Rochdale]] and [[Salford (hundred)|hundred of Salford]].<ref name="GM Gazetteer"/> Under [[feudalism]], Butterworth was governed by a number of ruling families, including the [[Baron Byron|Byrons]], who obtained the title of [[Lord of the Manor|Lords of the Manor]].<ref name="Hignett32"/> Throughout the [[Late Middle Ages]], local men acted as [[jurors]] and [[constables]] for the purposes of upholding law and order in Butterworth. Butterworth in the 19th century constituted a [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]], until its dissolution in 1894.<ref name="GM Gazetteer"/>

Milnrow's first [[local authority]] was a [[Local board of health]] established in 1870.<ref name="GM Gazetteer"/> Milnrow Local Board of Health was a regulatory body responsible for standards of hygiene and sanitation in the [[wards of the United Kingdom|wards]] of Belfield, Haugh and Milnrow.<ref name=fish122/> In 1879, a part of [[Castleton, Greater Manchester|Castleton]] and another part of Butterworth were included in the area of the Local board. Under the [[Local Government Act 1894]], the area of the local board broadly became the [[Milnrow Urban District]], a local government district in the Rochdale [[Poor Law Union]] and [[Administrative counties of England|administrative county]] of Lancashire.<ref name="GM Gazetteer"/> Under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], the Milnrow Urban District was abolished, and Milnrow has, since 1 April 1974, formed an [[unparished area]] of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Rochdale]], within the [[metropolitan county]] of [[Greater Manchester]].<ref name="GM Gazetteer"/> In anticipation of the new local government arrangement, Milnrow Urban District Council applied for [[successor parish]] status to be granted to the locality after 1974, but the application was not successful.<ref>{{Harvnb|Clark|1973|p=106.}}</ref> 

From 1983 to 1997, Milnrow was represented in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] as part of the [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|parliamentary constituency]] of [[Littleborough and Saddleworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Littleborough and Saddleworth]]. Between 1997 and 2010 it was within the boundaries of [[Oldham East and Saddleworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East and Saddleworth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdale.gov.uk/council_and_democracy/councillors,_democracy_and_ele/local_mps_and_meps_-_informati.aspx|author=Rochdale Metropolitan Borough Council|publisher=rochdale.gov.uk|accessdate=2008-04-22|title=Local MPs and MEPs - information and advice}}</ref> In 2010 Milnrow became part of the [[Rochdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochdale constituency]], which is represented by [[Simon Danczuk]] MP, a member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].

==Geography==
{{further2|[[Geography of Greater Manchester]]}}
[[Image:Newhey.jpg|thumb|300px|right|A view over Newhey and Milnrow, towards [[Rochdale]] and [[Wardle, Greater Manchester|Wardle]].]]
At {{coord|53|36|36|N|2|6|40|W|type:city}} (53.6101<U+00B0>, -2.1111<U+00B0>), and {{convert|168|mi|km|0}} north-northwest of [[central London]], Milnrow stands roughly {{convert|830|ft|m|0}} above [[sea level]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Milnrow, United Kingdom |work=Global Gazetteer, Version 2.1 |publisher=Falling Rain Genomics, Inc |url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/UK/0/Milnrow.html|accessdate=2008-01-02}}</ref> on the western slopes of the [[Pennines]], {{convert|10.4|mi|km|1}} north-northeast of [[Manchester city centre]], in the valley of the River Beal. [[Blackstone Edge]] and [[West Yorkshire]] are to the east; [[Rochdale]] and [[Shaw and Crompton]] are to the west and south respectively. Milnrow, considered as the area covered by the former Milnrow Urban District Council, extends over {{convert|8.1|sqmi|km2|0}}.<ref name="Hignett6">Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;6.</ref>

The River Beal, a tributary of the [[River Roch]], runs centrally through Milnrow from the south through [[Newhey]].<ref name="Hignett6"/> The soil is light gravel and clay, with subsoil of rough gravel,<ref name="County of Lanc">{{cite book |last=Brownbill|first=J|coauthors=William Farrer|title=A History of the County of Lancaster: Volume 5|publisher=Victoria County History|year=1911|pages=213<U+2013>222|isbn=978-0-7129-1055-2}}</ref> and the local [[geology]] is carboniferous [[coal measures]]. Milnrow's highest point ({{convert|1310|ft|m|0|disp=/}}) is by its east-southeastern border with the [[Metropolitan Borough of Oldham]] at [[Denshaw]] and Bleakedgate Moor, above the rugged, upland [[Piethorne Valley]] and close to [[Windy Hill (Pennines)|Windy Hill]]. From this point the average height of the land falls gradually towards the direction of Rochdale to the northwest, into a mixture of undulating farmland and [[suburb]]ia.<ref name=Roc33/><ref name="Hignett7">Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;7.</ref> Milnrow experiences a [[temperate]] [[Oceanic climate|maritime climate]], like much of the [[British Isles]], with relatively cool summers and mild winters. There is regular but generally light precipitation throughout the year. 
{{Geographic Location
|title     = '''Neighbouring cities, towns and places.'''
|Northwest = [[Wardle, Greater Manchester|Wardle]]
|North     = [[Littleborough, Greater Manchester|Littleborough]]
|Northeast = [[Blackstone Edge]]
|West      = [[Rochdale]]
|Centre    = Milnrow
|East      = [[Piethorne Valley]]
|Southwest = [[Thornham, Greater Manchester|Thornham]]
|South     = [[Shaw and Crompton]]
|Southeast = [[Newhey]]
}}

In 1855, the poet [[Edwin Waugh]] said of Milnow:{{quote|Milnrow lies on the ground not unlike a tall tree laid lengthwise, in a valley, by a riverside. At the bridge, its roots spread themselves in clots and fibrous shoots, in all directions; while the almost branchless trunk runs up, with a little bend, above half a mile towards Oldham, where it again spreads itself out in an umbrageous way.<ref name="Waugh">{{cite book|title=Sketches of Lancashire life and localities|last=Waugh|first=Edwin|authorlink=Edwin Waugh|year=1855|publisher=James Galt|page=61}}</ref>|[[Edwin Waugh]]|''Sketches of Lancashire life and localities'' (1855)}}

Surrounded by open moor and grassland on its northern and eastern sides, Milnrow forms a continuous urban area with neighbouring Rochdale to the west, and, according to the [[Office for National Statistics]], is part of the [[Greater Manchester Urban Area]], the United Kingdom's third largest conurbation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/downloads/census2001/ks_urban_north_part_5.pdf|format=PDF| title=Census 2001:Key Statistics for urban areas in the North; Map 3|author=[[Office for National Statistics]]|publisher=statistics.gov.uk|accessdate=2008-04-22|year=2001}}</ref>

There are a number of small named-places in and around Milnrow, including Clegg, Firgrove, Gallows, Haugh, Newhey, Kitcliffe, Ogden, and [[Tunshill]]. [[Newhey]], at the south of Milnrow by [[Shaw and Crompton]], is the most distinct of these areas, and, with its own [[parish church]] and railway station, is invariably given as a separate village. The Gallows [[public house]] is said to occupy the land of an ancient execution site; Gallows, a former hamlet at northeastern Milnrow, is named in reference to a [[baron]]ial [[gallows]].<ref name="RMBC32"/><ref name="Hignett3"/><ref>Lewis (1848), pp.&nbsp;729-733.</ref> Kitcliffe, Ogden and Tunshill, to the east of central Milnrow, are hamlets that occupy the upper, mid and lower [[Piethorne Valley]] respectively.

==Demography==
{{further2|[[Demography of Greater Manchester]]}}
According to the [[Office for National Statistics]], at the time of the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]], Milnrow (urban-core and sub-area) had a total resident population of 12,541.<ref>{{cite web |title=Greater Manchester Urban Area |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/census2001/greater_manchester_urban_area.asp |publisher=statistics.gov.uk |accessdate=2008-04-25|author=[[Office for National Statistics]]}}</ref> The [[Wards of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] of Milnrow (which has different boundaries) had a population of 11,561.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=5941592&c=milnrow&d=14&e=16&g=353369&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1209124581825&enc=1 |title=Milnrow (Ward)|author=United Kingdom Census 2001 |publisher=neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |accessdate=2008-04-28|year=2001}}</ref> ''[[Merriam-Webster's Geographical Dictionary]]'' (2007) estimated Milnrow's population to be 12,800 in 2001.<ref name=miln2/>

Of the residents in the electoral ward of Milnrow, which includes Newhey and the Piethorne Valley, 40.8% were married, 10.3% were [[Cohabitation|cohabiting]] couples, and 9.5% were lone parent families. Twenty-seven percent of households were made up of individuals and 13% had someone living alone at [[pension]]able age.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=5941592&c=milnrow&d=14&e=16&g=353369&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1209124581825&enc=1 |title=Milnrow (Ward): Household Composition |author=United Kingdom Census 2001 |publisher=neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |accessdate=2008-05-03|year=2001}}</ref> 

The [[Ethnic groups of the United Kingdom|ethnicity]] of the community was given as 98% white, 0.7% [[Multiracial|mixed race]], 0.8% Asian, 0.2% black and 0.3% Chinese or other.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941592&c=milnrow&d=14&e=15&g=353369&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1209774295962&enc=1&dsFamilyId=47|title=Milnrow (Ward): Ethnic Group |author=United Kingdom Census 2001 |publisher=neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |accessdate=2008-05-03|year=2001}}</ref>
The place of birth of the town's residents was 97% United Kingdom (including 95.04% from England), 0.6% [[Republic of Ireland]], 0.5% from other [[European Union]] countries, and 2.6% from elsewhere in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941592&c=milnrow&d=14&e=15&g=353369&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1209773249350&enc=1&dsFamilyId=11|title=Milnrow (Ward): Country of Birth|author=United Kingdom Census 2001 |publisher=neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |accessdate=2008-05-03|year=2001}}</ref> Religion was recorded as 80% Christian, 0.8% Muslim, 0.1% Hindu, 0.1% Buddhist, and 0.1% Jewish. Some 12.2% were recorded as having no religion, 0.2% had an alternative religion, and 6.1% did not state their religion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=5941592&c=milnrow&d=14&e=15&g=353369&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1209773035368&enc=1|title=Milnrow (Ward): Lead Key Figures|author=United Kingdom Census 2001 |publisher=neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |accessdate=2008-05-03|year=2001}}</ref> Historically, in addition to [[Church of England|the established church]], [[Nonconformism]] &ndash; particularly [[Wesleyanism]] &ndash; was a branch of [[Christian theology]] practised in Milnrow by a significant part of the local population.<ref>Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;34.</ref>

The economic activity of residents aged 16&ndash;74 was 45% in full-time employment, 12% in part-time employment, 7.7% self-employed, 2.6% unemployed, 2.1% students with jobs, 3.1% students without jobs, 13% retired, 4.6% looking after home or family, 7.4% permanently sick or disabled, and 2.3% economically inactive for other reasons. This was roughly in line with the national figures.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941592&c=milnrow&d=14&e=15&g=353369&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1209775102623&enc=1&dsFamilyId=21 |title=Milnrow (Ward): Economic Activity|author=United Kingdom Census 2001 |publisher=neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |accessdate=2008-05-03|year=2001}}</ref>

