==Economy==
[[File:Dale Street, Milnrow, Greater Manchester.jpg|thumb|right|Dale Street is Milnrow's main [[thoroughfare]] and the town's central business district.]]
Prior to [[deindustrialisation]] in the late-20th century, Milnrow's economy was linked closely with a spinning and weaving tradition which had evolved from developments in [[textile manufacture during the Industrial Revolution]]. Industries ancillary to textile production were also operational, such as [[coal mining]] at [[Tunshill]],<ref name="GMArch35"/> and [[metalworking]] at Butterworth Hall.<ref>{{Harvnb|Godman|1996|p=63}}.</ref> Butterworth Hall Colliery was the largest colliery in the Rochdale region, employing around 300 men in 1912.<ref name=Godman59>{{Harvnb|Godman|1996|p=59}}.</ref> Modern sectors in the area include [[engineering]], [[packaging]] materials, [[dye]]ing and finishing, and [[ink]] production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.link4life.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=c.showPage&pageID=925|publisher=link4life.org|author=Rochdale Boroughwide Cultural Trust|accessdate=2008-06-10|title=Milnrow & Newhey}}</ref> The main street comprises a variety of shops, restaurants and food outlets. 

The biggest employers are Holroyd Machine Tools, who have been based in the town since they moved from Manchester to Milnrow in 1896.<ref name=Godman62>{{Harvnb|Godman|1996|p=62}}.</ref> In the early 20th century they operated a [[foundry]] in Whitehall Street and employed engineers and apprentices.<ref name=Godman62/> As of 2006 Holroyd had a workforce of 160, but its parent company Renold PLC employs a further 200 people at a base in there.<ref name=buyers>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleobserver.co.uk/news/s/514/514817_buyers_are_all_set_to_move_in_on_company.html |title=Buyers are all set to move in on company|author=Foster, Stephen|publisher=rochdaleobserver.co.uk|date=2006-07-04|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleobserver.co.uk/community/rochdale_150/work/s/510/510701_in_gear_for_good_news_story_still_on_the_run.html |title=In gear for good news story still on the run|publisher=rochdaleobserver.co.uk|date=2006-03-20|author=Anon|accessdate=2008-04-22}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.renold.com/Company/Addresses/UnitedKingdom4.asp|publisher=renold.com|year=2004|accessdate=2003-04-29|title=Renold Gears, Rochdale}}</ref> Global industrial and consumer packaging company [[Sonoco]] operate a warehouse in the town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonoco.com/SonocoLocations/SearchEngine.asp|author=[[Sonoco Products]]|publisher=sonoco.com|accessdate=2008-04-22|title=Sonoco Locations}}</ref>

The Kingsway Business Park will be a {{convert|420|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} "business-focused, mixed use development" occupying land between Milnrow and Rochdale, adjacent to junction 21 of the [[M62 motorway]]; it is expected to employ 7,250 people directly and 1,750 people indirectly by around 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingswayuk.com/key_facts.php |title=Key Facts |accessdate=2008-06-15 |publisher=Kingsway }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> [[Kingsway Metrolink station]] is a station proposed in Phase 3a of the [[Manchester Metrolink]] expansion, and will serve Kingsway Business Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lrta.org/Manchester/Oldham_Rochdale.html|author=[[Light Rail Transit Association]]|title=Manchester to Oldham and Rochdale|accessdate=2008-10-31|date=2008-09-24|publisher=lrta.org}}</ref>

==Landmarks==
[[Image:St Thomas's, Newhey.jpg|thumb|right|upright|St Thomas's at [[Newhey]] has been described as "the most distinctive and splendid building in the district".]]

The [[listed building|Grade II listed]] Church of St James, Milnrow's [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] [[parish church]], was built in 1869 and is dedicated to [[James, son of Zebedee|James the Apostle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/Details/Default.aspx?id=439616&mode=quick|publisher=imagesofengland.org.uk|year=2001|accessdate=2008-05-01|title=Church of Saint James, Milnrow}}</ref> It is part of the [[Church of England]] and lies within the [[Anglican Diocese of Manchester|Diocese of Manchester]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchester.anglican.org/churches_detail.asp?ID=319|publisher=manchester.anglican.org|title=Milnrow, Saint James|accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref> The origins of the church can be traced to a [[chantry]] built by the [[Baron Byron|Byrons]] in the year 1400. When that baronial family moved from Milnrow to another of their homes following the [[Wars of the Roses]], the local population was left without a place of worship and a chapel was constructed by the [[River Beal]] to serve this community.<ref name="Hignett32"/> This structure existed until the 1790s, when a "poorly designed" chapel was erected and consecrated; however, due to structural weaknesses, that church was demolished in 1814.<ref name="Hignett32"/> Following an interim period when a "plain building" was used for worship, the present church building was built and consecrated by the [[Bishop of Manchester]] on 21 August 1869.<ref name="Hignett33"/>

Described as "by far the most distinctive and splendid building in the district",<ref name="Hignett33">Hignett, (1991), p.&nbsp;33.</ref> the [[Gothic Revival architecture|neo-Gothic]] Newhey, St Thomas parish church was built in 1876 and served a new Anglican parish of Newhey created in the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit_page.jsp?u_id=10355187&c_id=|publisher=visionofbritain.org.uk|title=A vision of Newhey EP|accessdate=2008-05-02}}</ref> Dedicated to [[Thomas the Apostle]], it is part of the Church of England, and its patron is the Bishop of Manchester.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53030|publisher=british-history.ac.uk |title=Townships - Butterworth|accessdate=2008-05-04}}</ref> The church was extensively damaged in an arson attack on 21 December 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleobserver.co.uk/news/s/1029652_church_hit_by_fire|publisher=rochdaleobserver.co.uk|date=2007-12-24|author= McKeegan, A. & Beckett, J.|title=Church hit by fire|accessdate=2008-06-10}}</ref>
[[Image:Milnrow War Memorial.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Milnrow War Memorial is a Grade II listed structure listing the men who fought and died in the two World Wars.]]
Milnrow War Memorial is located in Memorial Park at Newhey, and is a Grade II listed structure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/Details/Default.aspx?id=213440&mode=quick|title=Milnrow War Memorial|publisher=imagesofengland.org.uk|year=2001|accessdate=2008-04-23}}</ref> The [[war memorial]] was originally sited in central Milnrow, set back from the road near Milnrow Bridge, and was unveiled on 3 August 1924 by Major General A. Solly-Flood, a former commander of [[42nd (East Lancashire) Division]]. The memorial is constructed of sandstone surmounted by a bronze statue of a [[World War I]] [[infantry]] soldier with rifle and fixed [[bayonet]] symbolic of the young manhood of the district in the early days of World War I. In selecting the design the Milnrow War Memorial Committee was influenced by the statue unveiled at [[Waterhead, Greater Manchester|Waterhead in Oldham]]; the work of George Thomas. Thomas sculpted Milnrow's memorial in 1923. The plinth holds bronze and slate panels recording the names of those who died in the two World Wars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdale.gov.uk/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/memorial_-_maintenance.aspx |title=Memorial - maintenance |author=Rochdale Metropolitan Borough Council|publisher=rochdale.gov.uk|accessdate=2008-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pmsa.cch.kcl.ac.uk/MR/MR-ROC25.htm |title= Milnrow War Memorial |author=[[Public Monuments and Sculpture Association]] |date=2003-06-16 |accessdate=2007-04-03}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

[[Clegg Hall]] is a 17th-century hall and [[Grade II* listed buildings in Greater Manchester|Grade II* listed building]] situated in [[Open space reserve|green space]] between Milnrow, [[Rochdale]] and [[Littleborough, Greater Manchester|Littleborough]].<ref name="clegg hall">{{cite web |title=Clegg Hall |url=http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=46049&search=all&criteria=Milnrow |publisher=Pastscape.org.uk |accessdate=2008-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Clegg Hall |publisher=Images of England |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?id=213423 |accessdate=2007-12-18}}</ref> It was constructed in about 1610 for Theophilus Aston and may have been built on the site of a mediaeval house and inn.<ref name="clegg hall"/>

In Newhey is the Ellenroad Steam Museum, the retained engine house, boiler house, chimney and [[steam engine]] of Ellenroad Mill, a former 1892-built [[cotton mill]] designed by [[Sir Philip Stott, 1st Baronet]]. Now operated as an [[industrial heritage]] centre, the mill itself is no longer standing, but the steam engine (the world<U+2019>s largest working steam mill engine)<ref name="Ellenroad">{{cite web|url=http://www.industrialpowerhouse.co.uk/attractiondetail.asp?id=39|title=Ellenroad Steam Museum|publisher=industrialpowerhouse.co.uk|accessdate=2008-05-01 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070927192155/http://www.industrialpowerhouse.co.uk/attractiondetail.asp?id=39 |archivedate = September 27, 2007}}</ref> is maintained and steamed once a month by the Ellenroad Trust.<ref>McNeil, R. & Nevell, M. (2000), p.&nbsp;39.</ref> The museum has the only fully working cotton mill engine with its original steam-raising plant in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ellenroad.org.uk/|title=Welcome to Ellenroad!|publisher=ellenroad.org.uk|accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref> Ellenroad Mill produced fine cotton [[yarn]] using [[Spinning mule|mule spinning]].<ref name="Ellenroad"/>
 
[[Hollingworth Lake]] lies beyond Milnrow, by [[Littleborough, Greater Manchester|Littleborough]] and is part of a local [[country park]]. It was built in 1801 as a feeder reservoir for the [[Rochdale Canal]], but it soon became a tourist destination for local people during their leisure time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.link4life.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=c.showPage&pageID=621|publisher=link4life.org|title=Hollingworth Lake|accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref> The lake covers an area of {{convert|130|acre|km2}} and the path around it originally measured {{convert|2.5|mi|km|1}}.

==Transport==
[[File:Dale Street, Milnrow.jpg|thumb|right|A [[First Manchester]] bus passing through Milnrow]]

[[Public transport]] in Milnrow is co-ordinated by [[Transport for Greater Manchester]], and services include bus and rail transport. Major [[A roads in Great Britain|A roads]] link Milnrow with other settlements, including the [[A640 road]], which forms a route from Rochdale and over the Pennines into [[Huddersfield]] and [[West Yorkshire]]. 

[[Milnrow railway station]] was on the [[Oldham Loop Line]] which connected [[Manchester]], [[Oldham]] and [[Rochdale]].<ref name=Roc33/> The station was constructed in 1862 by [[navvies]] drafted by contractors under the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]. On 12 August 1863, the line was opened to commercial traffic and 2 November 1863, to passenger trains.<ref name="Hignett26">Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;26.</ref> Milnrow station was originally staffed, and the line through it was dual-track; however this section was reduced to single-track in 1980.<ref name="Hignett26"/> Milnrow railway station closed on 3 October 2009 to be converted for use with an expanded [[Manchester Metrolink]] network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/s/1150326_signalman_reaches_end_of_line|publisher=manchestereveningnews.co.uk|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|accessdate=2009-10-05|date=2009-10-01|title=Signalman reaches end of line|last=Kirby|first=Dean|ref=harv|postscript=.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/s/1069009_end_of_era_as_loop_line_is_replaced
|publisher=manchestereveningnews.co.uk|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|accessdate=2009-10-05|date=2008-09-26|title=End of era as loop line is replaced|ref=harv|postscript=.}}</ref> The station is planned to reopen in 2012 as [[Milnrow Metrolink station]]; also opening at this time will be [[Kingsway Metrolink station]] and [[New Hey railway station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lrta.org/Manchester/Oldham_Rochdale.html|publisher=lrta.org ork|title=Manchester to Oldham and Rochdale|author=Light Rail Transit Association|date=2007-11-24|accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref> 

Milnrow is situated at Junction 21 of the trans-Pennine [[M62 motorway]]. Construction of the Milnrow part of the M62 began in April 1967,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleobserver.co.uk/community/rochdale_150/motoring/s/514/514330_unlocking_the_door_to_heart_of_the_nation.html|title=Unlocking the door to heart of the nation|date=2006-06-17|accessdate=2008-04-25|publisher=rochdaleobserver.co.uk}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> a process which spread mud and dirt throughout the town.<ref name="Hignett35">Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;35.</ref> The official opening of the motorway on 13 October 1971 was by [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]], who was welcomed by [[Ralph Assheton, 1st Baron Clitheroe]] in his role as [[Lord Lieutenant of Lancashire]], as well as the Chairman of Milnrow Urban District Council and his wife.<ref name="Hignett35"/> Once opened, the Queen cast aside protocol for an informal meeting with the people of Milnrow.<ref name="Hignett35"/>

The [[Rochdale Canal]]&mdash;one of the major navigable broad [[canals of Great Britain]]&mdash;passes along Milnrow's north-western boundary which divides it from the village of [[Wardle, Greater Manchester|Wardle]] and districts of [[Belfield, Greater Manchester|Belfield]] and [[Castleton, Greater Manchester|Castleton]] in Rochdale.<ref name="Rochdale 1908">{{cite map|title=Rochdale|edition=1908|publisher=Alan Godfrey Maps|cartography=[[Ordnance Survey]]|isbn=1-84151-394-9 {{Please check ISBN|reason=Check digit (9) does not correspond to calculated figure.}}|section=Lancashire Sheet 89.01|year=2002}}</ref> The Rochdale Canal was historically used as a highway of commerce for the haulage of cotton, wool, and coal to and from the area.

Bus services operate to Rochdale, Newhey, Oldham, Manchester and Littleborough, mainly operated by [[First Manchester]].<ref name="RochdaleBusMap">{{cite web|title=Network Maps: Rochdale|url=http://www.gmpte.com/pdfmaps/network/rochdale.pdf|accessdate=2008-05-01|publisher=gmpte.com
|author=[[Greater Manchester Passenger Transport Executive]]|date=2008-04-30|format=PDF |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080414222654/http://www.gmpte.com/pdfmaps/network/rochdale.pdf |archivedate = April 14, 2008}}</ref>

==Education==
{{See also|List of schools in Rochdale}}
The Free School of Milnrow was founded in 1726. From 1739 until his death in 1786 the [[schoolmaster]] was the [[caricaturist]] [[John Collier (caricaturist)|John Collier]].<ref name="County of Lanc"/> Newhey Council School was constructed in 1911.<ref>Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;15.</ref> Milnrow St James School evolved into the modern [[primary school]], Milnrow Parish Church of England Primary.<ref>{{cite web |title=Milnrow Parish CofE Primary, Rochdale|url=http://www.milnrowparishce.rochdale.sch.uk/index.htm |publisher=milnrowparishce.rochdale.sch.uk|accessdate=2008-04-29}}</ref> It is a denominational school with the [[Church of England]], linked with Milnrow's [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] parish church, St James's. There are further primary schools, in central Milnrow named Moorhouse County Primary and Crossgates County Primary, and at Newhey named Newhey Community Primary, all of which are non-denominational.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newhey.rochdale.sch.uk/|publisher=newhey.rochdale.sch.uk|date=|accessdate=2008-04-29|title=Newhey Community Primary School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crossgates.rochdale.sch.uk/|publisher=crossgates.rochdale.sch.uk|title=Crossgates Primary School: Welcome to our school|date=|accessdate=2008-06-18}}</ref> Hollingworth Business and Enterprise College (formerly Hollingworth High) is a [[secondary school]] in Milnrow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollingworthbec.co.uk/|publisher=hollingworthbec.co.uk|title=Hollingworth Business and Enterprise College|accessdate=2008-05-02}}</ref> It is a [[co-educational]] school of non-denominational religion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.axcis.co.uk/28459.html|publisher=axcis.co.uk|title=Hollingworth High School, Rochdale |accessdate=2008-05-02|date=}}</ref> and was given [[Business and Enterprise College]] status under the [[Specialist school|Specialist School Programme]]. Other learning facilities in Milnrow include a 1907-built [[Carnegie library]].<ref name="Hignett7"/>

==Sports==

[[Milnrow C.C.]] is a [[cricket]] club based at Ladyhouse in Milnrow, and which has played in the [[Central Lancashire Cricket League]] since its foundation in 1892. Milnrow C.C. formed in 1857 from a group of local businessmen who felt the district deserved its own distinct team. Members of the club were recruited and teams were selected to play other clubs in the surrounding townships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milnrowcc.com/History.html|title=150 Years of History|publisher=milnrowcc.com|accessdate=2008-05-02}}</ref>

The Soccer Village consists of four indoor pitches in an arena with grandstand spectator seating for 300.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccervillage.net/|publisher=soccervillage.net|title=Welcome to The Soccer Village Website|accessdate=2008-05-02}}</ref> It is used for casual, amateur and organised leagues and tournaments. 

There has been a [[golf course]] at [[Tunshill]] since 1901.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tunshillgolfclub.co.uk/DesktopDefault.aspx/|title=Welcome to the Tunshill Golf Club Website |accessdate=2008-04-23|publisher=tunshillgolfclub.co.uk}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> It is affiliated with the [[English Golf Union]].

New Milnrow and Newhey Rugby League Club is the local [[Rugby league]] team.

==Public services==
[[Image:Piethorne Reservoir 1.jpg|thumb|right|Several reservoirs lie in Milnrow's Piethorne Valley (pictured), between [[Newhey]] and [[Denshaw]], including Rooden, Kitcliffe and Ogden.]]
[[Home Office]] policing in Milnrow is provided by the [[Greater Manchester Police]]. The force's "(P) Division" have their headquarters for policing the [[Metropolitan Borough of Rochdale]] in Rochdale and the nearest police station is at [[Littleborough, Greater Manchester|Littleborough]] to the north.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmp.police.uk/division11/pages/pennine.htm|title=Pennine policing area|author=[[Greater Manchester Police]]|publisher=gmp.police.uk|date=2006-01-26|accessdate=2008-04-22 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071107105703/http://www.gmp.police.uk/division11/pages/pennine.htm |archivedate = November 7, 2007}}</ref> [[Fire service in the United Kingdom|Statutory emergency fire and rescue service]] is provided by the [[Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service]], which has one station in Rochdale on Maclure Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchesterfire.gov.uk/my-area/rochdale.aspx|publisher=manchesterfire.gov.uk|author=[[Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service]]|accessdate=2008-03-07|title=My area: Rochdale |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080306003130/http://www.manchesterfire.gov.uk/my-area/rochdale.aspx |archivedate = March 6, 2008}}</ref>

There are no hospitals in Milnrow&mdash;the nearest are in the larger settlements of Oldham and Rochdale. The Rochdale Infirmary in north-central Rochdale and Birch Hill Hospital near the villages of [[Wardle, Greater Manchester|Wardle]] and [[Littleborough, Greater Manchester|Littleborough]], are [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]] hospitals administrated by [[Pennine Acute Hospitals NHS Trust]]. Birch Hill occupies the former Rochdale Union [[Workhouse]] at Dearnley.<ref name="Workhouse">{{cite web|url=http://www.workhouses.org.uk/index.html?Rochdale/Rochdale.shtml|publisher=workhouses.org.uk|author=Higginbotham, Peter|title=Rochdale|date=2007-05-07|accessdate=2008-03-07}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The [[North West Ambulance Service]] provides emergency patient transport. 

[[Waste management]] is co-ordinated by the [[local authority]] via the [[Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmwda.gov.uk/|title=Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority (GMWDA)|publisher=gmwda.gov.uk|author=[[Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority]]|year=2008|accessdate=2008-02-08}}</ref> Milnrow's [[Distribution Network Operator]] for electricity is [[United Utilities]];<ref name="UU">{{cite web|url=http://www.unitedutilities.com/?OBH=413&SCH=rochdale&ID=1416|title=Rochdale|publisher=unitedutilities.com|author=[[United Utilities]]|date=2007-04-06|accessdate=2008-02-08}}</ref> there are no [[power station]]s in the area, but a [[Wind farm]] exists on Scout Moor which consists of 26 turbines on the high moors between [[Rawtenstall]] and Rochdale, generating 65[[Megawatt|MW]] of electricity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scoutmoorwindfarm.co.uk/indexorig.html|publisher=scoutmoorwindfarm.co.uk|title=Scout Moor Wind Farm|accessdate=2008-03-02 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080209124954/http://www.scoutmoorwindfarm.co.uk/indexorig.html |archivedate = February 9, 2008}}</ref> United Utilities also manages Milnrow's [[drinking water|drinking]] and [[waste water]];<ref name="UU"/> water supplies are sourced from several local reservoirs, including [[Kitcliffe Reservoir|Kitcliffe]], [[Piethorne Reservoir|Piethorne]] and [[Rooden Reservoir|Rooden]] in Milnrow's outlying moorland between [[Newhey]] and [[Denshaw]].<ref name="UU"/>

==Notable people==
{{See also|List of people from Rochdale}}
[[John Collier (caricaturist)|John Collier]] (who wrote under the pseudonym of Tim Bobbin) was an acclaimed 18th-century [[caricaturist]] and satirical poet who was raised and spent all his adult life in Milnrow. Born in [[Urmston]] in 1708, Collier was [[schoolmaster]] for Milnrow. Inspired by [[William Hogarth]], Collier's work savagely lampooned the behaviour of [[upper class|upper]] and [[lower class]]es alike, and was written in a strong [[Lancashire dialect and accent|Lancashire dialect]].<ref>Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;39.</ref> Many of his works and personal possessions are preserved in Milnrow's library,<ref>Rochdale Metropolitan Borough Council (N.D.), p.&nbsp;33.</ref> and he is commemorated in the name of a "prominent pub" in central Milnrow.<ref name=Roc33/> [[Francis Robert Raines]] (1805<U+2013>1878) was the Anglican vicar of Milnrow, and an antiquary. He edited 23 volumes for the Chetham Society publications.<ref name="Raines">{{cite web|url=http://www.lan-opc.org.uk/Milnrow/ministers.html|publisher=www.lan-opc.org.uk|accessdate=2008-11-03|title=Early Ministers of Milnrow}}</ref> He was ordained in 1828, and after short appointments at [[Saddleworth]] and Rochdale, he was vicar at Milnrow for the rest of his life.<ref name="Raines"/> [[John Milne]] was a professor, [[geologist]] and mining [[engineer]] who invented a pioneering [[seismograph]] (known as the Milne-Shaw seismograph) to detect and measure earthquakes. Although born in [[Liverpool]] in 1850 owing to a brief visit there by his parents, Milne was raised in Rochdale and at Tunshill in Milnrow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleobserver.co.uk/news/s/1021736_famous_scientists_on_road_to_name_wrangle|title=Famous scientists on road to name wrangle|date=2007-10-27|author=McKeegan, Alice|publisher=rochdaleobserver.co.uk|accessdate=2008-04-25}}</ref><ref>Hignett (1991), p.&nbsp;38.</ref> Other notable people of Milnrow include [[Lizzy Bardsley]], who, in 2003, gained fame from appearing on [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[Wife Swap (UK TV series)|Wife Swap]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleobserver.co.uk/news/s/333/333776_wifeswap_lizzy_insists_im_a_star.html|title=Wife-swap Lizzy insists: 'I'm a star'|date=2003-10-14|accessdate=2008-04-25|author=Hopton, Katie|publisher=rochdaleobserver.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/4016233.stm|title='Wife Swap' star's benefit charge|publisher=[[BBC News|news.bbc.co.uk]]|date=2004-11-16|accessdate=2008-06-10}}</ref>

